This report explores trends and disparities in under-5 mortality across countries, continents, and genders using UNICEF data.

import polars as pl
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, labs, theme_minimal

# Load and prepare data in Polars
df = pl.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")
df = df.rename({col: col.strip() for col in df.columns})
df = df.filter(pl.col("indicator").str.to_lowercase().str.contains("mortality"))
df = df.drop_nulls(subset=["obs_value", "time_period", "country"])

# Group by year and calculate average mortality
avg_df = df.group_by("time_period").agg(
    pl.col("obs_value").mean().alias("avg_mortality")
).sort("time_period")

# Convert to pandas for plotnine
avg_df_pd = avg_df.to_pandas()
avg_df_pd["time_period"] = avg_df_pd["time_period"].astype(int)

# Plot with regression line
from plotnine import ggplot, aes, geom_point, geom_smooth, labs, theme_minimal

plot = (
    ggplot(avg_df_pd, aes(x="time_period", y="avg_mortality"))
    + geom_point(color="#0072B2", size=3)
    + geom_smooth(method="lm", se=True, color="red")
    + labs(
        title="Trend of Average Under-5 Mortality Rate Over Time",
        x="Year",
        y="Average Under-5 Mortality Rate"
    )
    + theme_minimal()
    + theme(
    plot_title=element_text(color='white'),
    axis_title_x=element_text(color='white'),
    axis_title_y=element_text(color='white'),
    axis_text_x=element_text(color='white'),
    axis_text_y=element_text(color='white'),
    legend_text=element_text(color='white'),
    legend_title=element_text(color='white')
)

)

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load UNICEF data
df = pd.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")

# Clean column names
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip()

# Filter for Under-5 mortality only
mortality_df = df[df["indicator"].str.contains("mortality", case=False)]

# Use most recent year (2022)
latest_year = mortality_df["time_period"].max()

# Filter for latest year
mortality_2022 = mortality_df[mortality_df["time_period"] == latest_year]

# Keep only relevant columns
mortality_2022 = mortality_2022[["alpha_3_code", "obs_value", "country"]].rename(
    columns={
        "alpha_3_code": "iso_a3",
        "obs_value": "under5_mortality",
        "country": "country_name"
    }
)

# Merge with shapefile GeoDataFrame
world_merged = world.merge(mortality_2022, how="left", left_on="ISO_A3", right_on="iso_a3")

ð Mortality Rate Trend over time according to Continents

This scatter plot shows per-country mortality across time, color-coded by continent. Regression lines capture overall trends, showing steady improvement globally even though some continents lag behind.

Code 
import polars as pl
import pandas as pd
import pycountry
import pycountry_convert as pc
from plotnine import *

# Load data
df = pl.read_csv("unicef_indicator_1.csv")
df = df.rename({col: col.strip() for col in df.columns})
df = df.filter(pl.col("indicator").str.to_lowercase().str.contains("mortality"))
df = df.drop_nulls(subset=["obs_value", "time_period", "country"])

# === Map country to continent ===
def get_continent(country_name):
    try:
        country = pycountry.countries.get(name=country_name)
        if not country:
            country = pycountry.countries.search_fuzzy(country_name)[0]
        alpha2 = country.alpha_2
        cont_code = pc.country_alpha2_to_continent_code(alpha2)
        return pc.convert_continent_code_to_continent_name(cont_code)
    except:
        return None

unique_countries = df.select("country").unique().to_series().to_list()
continent_df = pl.DataFrame({
    "country": unique_countries,
    "continent": [get_continent(c) for c in unique_countries]
}).drop_nulls()

# Join continent info
df_continent = df.join(continent_df, on="country", how="left").drop_nulls(subset=["continent"])

# Convert to pandas for plotnine
df_scatter = df_continent.to_pandas()
df_scatter["time_period"] = df_scatter["time_period"].astype(int)

# === Scatterplot with regression line per continent ===
scatter_continent = (
    ggplot(df_scatter, aes(x="time_period", y="obs_value", color="continent")) +
    geom_point(alpha=0.4, size=1.5) +
    geom_smooth(method="lm", se=False) +
    labs(
        title="Under-5 Mortality Rate Over Time by Continent",
        x="Year",
        y="Mortality Rate",
        color="Continent"
    ) +
    theme_minimal()
    + theme(
    plot_title=element_text(color='white'),
    axis_title_x=element_text(color='white'),
    axis_title_y=element_text(color='white'),
    axis_text_x=element_text(color='white'),
    axis_text_y=element_text(color='white'),
    legend_text=element_text(color='white'),
    legend_title=element_text(color='white')
)

)

scatter_continent

ð Conclusion & Call to Action

This analysis reveals critical insights into the global landscape of under-5 mortality rates. We observed significant variations across continents, time periods, and gender, highlighting persistent inequalities in child health outcomes. While overall mortality rates have declined over time, regions such as Africa continue to bear a disproportionate burden, demanding urgent and focused interventions.

To accelerate progress and ensure every child has a fair chance at life, we must prioritize the following call to action items:

  • Invest in Maternal & Neonatal Care: Strengthen access to prenatal, delivery, and postnatal careâespecially in low-income and high-risk regions.
  • Improve Vaccination Coverage: Expand immunization programs to prevent infectious diseases that disproportionately affect young children.
  • Promote Gender Equity in Healthcare Access: Ensure both male and female children receive equal attention and care from birth.
  • Support Community-Based Health Workers: Empower local health agents to deliver life-saving interventions in underserved areas.
  • Address Malnutrition & Food Security: Tackle undernutrition through education, food programs, and targeted support for vulnerable populations.
  • Leverage Data for Policy Action: Use real-time data and analytics to identify gaps, track progress, and adapt strategies in a timely manner.

Ending preventable child deaths is not only possibleâit is a moral imperative. Through collaborative efforts, sustainable investment, and data-driven policies, we can move closer to achieving the global goal of reducing under-5 mortality and ensuring a healthier, more equitable future for all children.
